The Ebola outbreak in the Democratic Republic of Congo has claimed more than 2 000 lives, out of a total of 3 000 recorded cases since August last year, health officials said on Friday. "In total, there have been 2 006 deaths (1 901 confirmed and 105 probable)," officials said in a bulletin dated Thursday. "Since the start of the epidemic, the number of cases is 3 004, including 2 899 confirmed and 105 probable," it added. GET THE NEWS at your fingertips and download the News24 app for Android here now. Get it for your iPhone here. DRC: Lake Kivu's waters essential in the fight against ebola The fight against Ebola in Goma, a commercial hub facing severe water shortages in eastern Democratic Republic of Congo, depends on the generosity of Lake Kivu, which supplies water to health teams. KEEP UPDATED on the latest news by subscribing to our FREE newsletter. - FOLLOW News24 on Twitter 